2.3 Generating a Scatter Plot Using geom_point()

library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)
library(scales)

# Load the dataset
resale_flats <- read.csv("ResaleFlatPrices/Resale Flat Prices (Based on Approval Date), 1990 - 1999.csv")

# Filter dataset for Ang Mo Kio town only
amk_flats <- resale_flats %>%
  filter(town == "ANG MO KIO")  

num_observations <- nrow(amk_flats)  # Correct function
cat("Number of observations:", num_observations, "\n")
Number of observations: 20477 
# Generate scatter plot for Ang Mo Kio resale flats
ggplot(amk_flats, aes(x = floor_area_sqm, y = resale_price)) +
  geom_point() +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = comma_format()) +
  labs(
    title = "Scatter Plot of Floor Area vs. Resale Price (Ang Mo Kio)",
    x = "Floor Area (sqm)",
    y = "Resale Price (SGD)",
    caption = "Data Source: Singapore Department of Statistics"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()

2.4 Producing and Discussing Two Distinct Plots Designed to Mitigate Overplotting

2.4.1 1. Scatter Plot with Transparency

ggplot(amk_flats, aes(x = floor_area_sqm, y = resale_price)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.1) +  # Reduces opacity to show density
  scale_y_continuous(labels = comma_format()) +
  labs(
    title = "Scatter Plot with Transparency (Ang Mo Kio)",
    x = "Floor Area (sqm)",
    y = "Resale Price (SGD)",
    caption = "Data Source: Singapore Department of Statistics"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()

2.4.2 2. Scatter Plot with Jittering

ggplot(amk_flats, aes(x = floor_area_sqm, y = resale_price)) +
  geom_jitter(width = 2, height = 5000, alpha = 0.2) +  # Adds randomness to spread points
  scale_y_continuous(labels = comma_format()) +
  labs(
    title = "Scatter Plot with Jittering (Ang Mo Kio)",
    x = "Floor Area (sqm)",
    y = "Resale Price (SGD)",
    caption = "Data Source: Singapore Department of Statistics"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()
